\title{Pedestrian Trajectory Prediction and World Modelling for Safe Robot Navigation in Human Crowds}

\author{
\IEEEauthorblockN{Vaibhav Mehra \quad Muhammad Maaz \quad Benjamin Li}
\IEEEauthorblockA{
Department of Computer Science\\
University College London\\
London, United Kingdom\\
\{vaibhav.mehra.23, muhammad.maaz.23, benjamin.li.23\}@ucl.ac.uk}
}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Safe robot navigation in human crowds depends on predicting uncertain
pedestrian motion before planning or runtime safety filtering can make
reliable decisions. Building on our earlier survey, which identified a gap
between open-loop prediction quality and closed-loop navigation safety, this
report presents a prediction-centered stack with three connected parts:
synthetic trajectory augmentation, a residual crowd world model, and a
benchmark of trajectory predictors. The implementation includes a Social-CVAE generator
pretrained on SDD and fine-tuned on ETH/UCY, a lightweight world model that
predicts pedestrian futures as a learned residual over constant velocity, and
five predictors: Social-LSTM, SLSTM+V, Social-GRU, a Trajectory Transformer,
and a diffusion predictor, evaluated against constant velocity and
Trajectron++. On held-out eth, the Simple Residual Model improves ADE from
1.0755 m to 0.9514 m and FDE from 2.2819 m to 1.9171 m. On ETH/UCY, the
Transformer gives the lowest ADE, 0.568 m, and NLL, 1.54, while Trajectron++
gives the lowest minADE@20, 0.385 m. SDD pretraining improves recurrent models
by 5 to 10 percent. Filtered synthetic data supports augmentation but requires
quality control.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
trajectory prediction, world models, pedestrian motion, synthetic data,
transformers, diffusion models, crowd navigation
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

Mobile robots operating in corridors, hospitals, stations, campuses, or
shopping spaces must move through people who are not passive obstacles. People
slow down, turn, give way, ignore the robot, or react late. The navigation
problem is therefore more than geometric collision avoidance; it requires
forecasting uncertain human motion quickly enough for a downstream planner and
safety layer to use it.

The earlier literature review surveyed crowd navigation methods and found a recurring
systems problem: better module-level prediction does not automatically imply
safer closed-loop navigation. Point forecasts can look accurate under ADE/FDE
while missing rare but safety-critical futures; diverse forecasts can cover
more futures but produce uncertainty sets so large that planning becomes
conservative; and more complex models can miss real-time control budgets. Those
findings motivated the work in this report. Instead of repeating the survey, we
focus on the design, implementation, and evaluation of the prediction and world
modelling components built so far.

The project is framed as a prediction-centered crowd navigation stack.
Vaibhav developed a Social-CVAE synthetic trajectory generator and a residual
crowd world model. The generator increases training diversity, while the world
model gives a lightweight planning-facing forecast by correcting a
constant-velocity physical prior. Muhammad implemented and evaluated the
trajectory prediction suite, including recurrent, Transformer, diffusion, and
Trajectron++ baselines, plus SDD pretraining and ETH/UCY fine-tuning.
Benjamin's work connects the prediction stack to downstream navigation safety
through a conformal/PPO safety-planning interface; since final safety results
are not available in this repository, that component is treated as integration
context and future closed-loop validation, not as evaluated output.

The report makes three contributions. First, it evaluates whether synthetic
trajectories can augment scarce ETH/UCY data without replacing real pedestrian
motion. Second, it tests a residual crowd world model as a simple model of
pedestrian dynamics for planning. Third, it compares multiple trajectory
predictors under a shared protocol on ETH/UCY and SDD, then studies whether
SDD pretraining and synthetic fine-tuning improve generalisation.

\subsection{Design Rationale From The Initial Survey}

The initial literature survey shaped the implementation in three concrete ways.
The first was the need to treat pedestrian motion as multi-modal. A person walking toward an
intersection may continue straight, slow down, turn, or avoid another person.
Single-trajectory predictors can score well when the most common future occurs,
but they do not tell a planner whether an alternative future is still plausible.
For this reason, the benchmark compares point-prediction models with
Trajectron++ and a diffusion predictor, and reports both ADE/FDE and
best-of-20 metrics.

The second design lesson was that prediction uncertainty must be usable by the
downstream system. A model that produces accurate means but poorly calibrated
uncertainty can make a conformal safety layer either overconfident or
unnecessarily conservative. The report therefore includes NLL where available
and discusses how residual errors would feed conformal regions. The objective
is to provide uncertainty that can be converted into planning constraints, not
only to forecast pedestrians for a benchmark.

The third lesson was the real-time constraint. In a crowd navigation stack,
predictions must be recomputed as the robot replans. A heavy model that improves
open-loop prediction but lowers the achieved control frequency can harm the
closed-loop system. The benchmark therefore includes lightweight baselines such as
constant velocity and the residual world model alongside larger neural
predictors. The comparison is therefore not simply between old and new models,
but between different assumptions about speed, diversity, calibration, and
planning suitability.

\section{Project Management}

The initial project plan split the work into four deliverables. D1 was a
multi-modal prediction module, D2 an interaction-aware planning component, D3 a
confidence-calibrated safety layer, and D4 an end-to-end evaluation suite. By
the time of this report, the most complete evidence is in D1 and its
supporting components: synthetic augmentation, residual world modelling, and
predictor evaluation. The planning and safety layer remains the downstream
interface into which these predictions will be integrated.

