The role split also evolved as the implementation matured. Vaibhav focused on
the Social-CVAE generator and residual world model, including the generation
pipeline, filtering criteria, and held-out eth residual-model evaluation.
Muhammad implemented the trajectory prediction benchmark and transfer-learning
experiments, including Social-LSTM, SLSTM+V, Social-GRU, the Trajectory
Transformer, diffusion predictor, SDD training, and ETH/UCY fine-tuning.
Benjamin's role is the safety/planning bridge, where predictor outputs feed
conformal uncertainty handling and PPO-based navigation. His contribution
defines how the forecasts produced by the prediction stack become action-level
safety constraints: sampled or Gaussian pedestrian futures are converted into
uncertainty regions, the nominal policy proposes a robot action, and the
safety interface can veto or reshape unsafe actions before execution. This
keeps the report aligned with the original safe-navigation goal even though the
numerical results available in this repository are most complete for prediction and
world modelling.

The main risks were dependency setup, limited compute, integration mismatch,
and modest performance gains. Setup risk was mitigated by keeping models and
data loaders modular. Compute risk was handled by using leave-one-scene-out
training, early stopping, and smaller predictor variants before running larger
models. Integration risk remains open: the prediction components are ready, but
full closed-loop testing still requires connecting them to Benjamin's safety
and planning stack. Finally, because high-capacity models do not always
outperform simpler baselines, the report includes negative and mixed findings
as well as the best-performing results.

\subsection{Deliverable Status}

D1 is complete for this submission. It includes constant velocity,
Social-LSTM, SLSTM+V, Social-GRU, Transformer, diffusion, and Trajectron++
comparisons on ETH/UCY, plus SDD training and a fine-tuning study. D1 also
benefits from Vaibhav's synthetic data pipeline because the fine-tuning stage
uses filtered synthetic trajectories as an augmentation source.

D2 is complete at the modelling/interface level for this report: the residual
crowd world model produces planning-facing forecasts, and Benjamin's
safety-planning interface specifies how those forecasts are consumed by a
nominal policy. D3 is complete as an implementation design and interface:
prediction residuals and sampled futures are the inputs to conformal uncertainty
handling, while PPO-based navigation provides the nominal action stream. D4 is
complete for the current scope as an evaluation suite for prediction, synthetic
augmentation, transfer, and world modelling. Full closed-loop collision-rate,
time-to-goal, and conservatism measurements are the next evaluation layer after
the components are connected in simulation.

\section{Methodology and System Design}

\subsection{System Overview}

Fig.~\ref{fig:system_overview} shows the stack used in this report. The first
stage expands the data distribution through synthetic trajectory generation.
The second stage learns a residual crowd world model for planning-facing
pedestrian motion forecasts. The third stage benchmarks several trajectory
predictors, some optimized for point accuracy and others for stochastic
coverage. These outputs are intended to feed a downstream conformal safety
layer, where calibrated prediction errors determine how much space must be
reserved around future human positions~\cite{angelopoulos2021gentle}.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \resizebox{0.70\columnwidth}{!}{\input{figures/pipeline}}
  \caption{Synthetic data and world-model pipeline used to support downstream
  predictor training and eventual safety-aware navigation.}
  \label{fig:system_overview}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Synthetic Data Generation}

ETH/UCY is the target benchmark, but it contains only five scenes and a limited
range of crowd configurations. To increase data scale and motion diversity, we
developed a Social-CVAE generator. Synthetic data is used as augmentation, not
as a replacement for real trajectories.

The generator follows the standard 8-step observation and 12-step prediction
format. It is pretrained on SDD~\cite{robicquet2016learning}, which provides a
larger and broader aerial pedestrian dataset, then fine-tuned on ETH/UCY so the
generated samples better match the target benchmark distribution. The CVAE
structure is appropriate because the same observed path can plausibly lead to
several futures: continuing straight, slowing down, turning, or reacting to
nearby pedestrians. The latent variable models this ambiguity.

The preprocessing stage converts both SDD and ETH/UCY into fixed-length
trajectory windows and normalises them into a shared coordinate convention. Each
training sample contains the target pedestrian history, its future trajectory,
and nearby pedestrian histories when available. During training, the encoder can
condition on the observed future through the approximate posterior
$q_\phi(z\mid x,y,h)$; during generation, only the observed past and social
context are available, so samples are drawn from the conditional prior
$p_\theta(z\mid x,h)$. This distinction matters because it prevents the
generator from depending on information that would not exist at deployment.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \resizebox{0.82\columnwidth}{!}{\input{figures/social_cvae}}
  \caption{Social-CVAE generator. The posterior uses future trajectories during
  training; at generation time, the conditional prior samples futures from the
  observed trajectory and social context.}
  \label{fig:cvae}
\end{figure}

The training objective was
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
\mathcal{L} =
&\mathcal{L}_{\text{recon}}
+ \lambda_v \mathcal{L}_{\text{vel}} \\
&+ \beta D_{\text{KL}}(q_\phi(z)\,\|\,p_\theta(z))
+ \lambda_s \mathcal{L}_{\text{smooth}} .
\end{split}
\end{equation}
This combines position reconstruction, velocity consistency, latent
regularisation, and trajectory smoothness. For each seed trajectory, we
generated 20 candidate futures. Angle-based filtering removes
unrealistic samples such as overly straight, overly smooth, or unstable
trajectories. This step is important because poor synthetic samples can widen
the training distribution away from realistic pedestrian motion.

The filtering stage is part of the model design. Synthetic data should increase
support around plausible pedestrian behaviours without making unrealistic
curves appear likely to the downstream predictor. Vaibhav's pipeline keeps
synthetic trajectories as a train-only augmentation source: the validation and
test sets remain real ETH/UCY scenes, so performance cannot be inflated by
testing on generated data.

\subsection{Residual Crowd World Model}

The residual crowd world model is a separate contribution from the predictor
benchmark. Its purpose is to provide a lightweight planning-facing dynamics
model for nearby pedestrian motion. It predicts 12 future timesteps from 8
observed timesteps, matching the ETH/UCY setup, but it does not learn the full
trajectory from scratch. Instead, it corrects a physical baseline:
\begin{equation}
\hat{Y}=Y_{\text{CV}}+R_\theta(X,S),
\label{eq:residual_model}
\end{equation}
where $Y_{\text{CV}}$ is the constant-velocity forecast, $R_\theta$ is the
learned residual, $X$ is the observed target trajectory, and $S$ is optional
nearby pedestrian context.

This design choice is conservative. Pedestrians often move
smoothly over a few seconds, so constant velocity is a strong prior. The neural
network only needs to learn deviations: turning, slowing down, acceleration,
or local interaction effects. Trajectories are shifted into a local frame using
the last observed position as origin. A GRU encodes the target trajectory;
neighbours are encoded and mean-pooled with a validity mask; and the fused
representation is decoded into a residual correction.

Three variants separate the benefit of residual learning from
the benefit of extra context or capacity. The Simple Residual Model uses only
the target pedestrian history and tests whether a learned correction to constant
velocity is sufficient. The Social Residual Model adds nearby pedestrian
context, testing whether interaction cues improve prediction. The Latent Crowd
World Model adds a higher-capacity latent dynamics representation, testing
whether a more expressive world model improves generalisation or overfits the
small ETH/UCY training split.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \resizebox{0.82\columnwidth}{!}{\input{figures/world_model}}
  \caption{Residual crowd world model. The final pedestrian forecast combines a
  constant-velocity prior with a learned residual correction from target and
  social context.}
  \label{fig:world_model}
\end{figure}

The model was trained with
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}
=
\mathcal{L}_{\text{ADE}}
+ \lambda_f \mathcal{L}_{\text{FDE}}
+ \lambda_r \mathcal{L}_{\text{res}} .
\end{equation}
ADE encourages full-horizon accuracy, FDE emphasizes the final position, and
residual regularisation discourages unrealistic corrections.

This world model is separate from the larger predictor
benchmark. The benchmark asks which forecasting architecture performs best under
standard open-loop metrics. The world model asks a planning-facing question:
can a lightweight, interpretable dynamics model improve over a hand-designed
physical prior while remaining simple enough to use inside a future control
loop?

\subsection{Trajectory Prediction Models}
\label{sec:tpm}

The predictor benchmark evaluates models that output future pedestrian
trajectories for downstream planning and safety filtering. Each predictor
observes 8 steps at 2.5 Hz (3.2 s) and predicts 12 future steps (4.8 s).
Coordinates are represented relative to the last observed position, which
reduces dependence on absolute scene location~\cite{alahi2016social}. Social
context comes from up to five neighbours inside a 2.0 m radius, with validity
masks used when fewer neighbours are present. Except for the constant-velocity
and Trajectron++ baselines, models output a bivariate Gaussian
$(\mu_x,\mu_y,\sigma_x,\sigma_y,\rho)$ per future step and are trained with
negative log-likelihood plus ADE/FDE monitoring. This common interface makes the
comparison fair: each model sees the same history and social context, but uses a
different inductive bias.

Social-LSTM~\cite{alahi2016social} is the recurrent baseline. It uses an
LSTM encoder-decoder with hidden size 128, embedding size 64, and social pooling
over nearby pedestrian hidden states. SLSTM+V keeps the same architecture but
appends instantaneous velocity
\begin{equation}
v_t=p_t-p_{t-1}
\end{equation}
to the focal pedestrian input, changing $(x_t,y_t)$ into
$(x_t,y_t,v_x,v_y)$ while leaving neighbour inputs as positions. This tests a
small but important design question: whether giving the model explicit
short-term motion state improves forecasting more reliably than asking the LSTM
to infer velocity from positions alone. Social-GRU replaces the LSTM with a
bidirectional GRU~\cite{cho2014learning,schuster1997bidirectional}. Forward and
backward states are concatenated and projected into the shared hidden
representation, allowing late observation cues, such as a pedestrian beginning
to decelerate near the end of the history, to influence the encoded trajectory.

The Trajectory Transformer uses a Pre-LN encoder-decoder
architecture~\cite{vaswani2017attention,xiong2020layer}. Eight focal tokens and
up to forty neighbour tokens form the encoder memory; twelve learned decoder
queries cross-attend to that memory and output bivariate Gaussian parameters
for each future step. This structure gives each predicted timestep direct
access to the complete observed social scene.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \resizebox{0.62\columnwidth}{!}{\input{figures/transformer}}
  \caption{Trajectory Transformer architecture used in the prediction benchmark.}
  \label{fig:transformer}
\end{figure}

The diffusion predictor uses a shared Transformer encoder, a Gaussian MLP head,
and a denoiser trained with a DDPM loss~\cite{ho2020denoising}. A CLS summary
feeds the Gaussian head, while the denoiser cross-attends to the encoded
trajectory memory and predicts the noise term for a candidate future. The implementation uses
100 diffusion steps, linear $\beta \in [10^{-4},0.02]$, DDIM-50 sampling at
inference~\cite{song2021denoising}, and $K=20$ samples for diversity metrics.
An early implementation detached the Gaussian head from the shared encoder; the
final version removes this detach so that the likelihood and denoising losses
jointly shape the representation.
Trajectron++~\cite{salzmann2020trajectron} is included as the main probabilistic
multi-modal baseline because its graph-structured CVAE directly models
multi-agent trajectory distributions.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{Main predictor design choices.}
\label{tab:model_design}
\centering
\scriptsize
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.12}
\begin{tabularx}{\columnwidth}{@{}p{1.65cm}X p{1.55cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Model} & \textbf{Role in the comparison} & \textbf{Output} \\
\midrule
CV & Non-learned physical baseline and residual-model prior. & Mean plus noise \\
Social-LSTM & Recurrent social-pooling baseline from prior work. & Gaussian \\
SLSTM+V & Tests whether explicit velocity improves Social-LSTM. & Gaussian \\
Social-GRU & Tests bidirectional recurrent encoding under same social radius. & Gaussian \\
Transformer & Tests full-window attention over focal and neighbour tokens. & Gaussian \\
Diffusion & Tests stochastic sampling with a denoising trajectory model. & Samples plus Gaussian head \\
Trajectron++ & Probabilistic graph-CVAE baseline for multi-modal coverage. & Samples/GMM \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\subsection{Transfer Learning}
\label{sec:transfer}

ETH/UCY is small, so the project uses a two-stage transfer protocol. Stage one pretrains
each architecture on SDD for up to 100 epochs with Adam at learning rate
$10^{-3}$. Stage two fine-tunes each checkpoint on the four ETH/UCY training
scenes plus filtered synthetic trajectories for up to 50 epochs at learning
rate $10^{-4}$, with early stopping and gradient clipping. The goal is to use
SDD for broad motion statistics, ETH/UCY for target-domain realism, and
synthetic trajectories for additional crowd configurations. This protocol also
tests whether Vaibhav's generated trajectories improve Muhammad's predictor
training, instead of evaluating the generator only as a standalone component.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \resizebox{0.62\columnwidth}{!}{\input{figures/finetune_pipeline}}
  \caption{Two-stage transfer: SDD pretraining followed by ETH/UCY and synthetic
  fine-tuning.}
  \label{fig:finetune}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Downstream Safety Interface}

The prediction stack is designed to feed a safety-aware navigation layer rather
than operate as an isolated benchmark. In the intended integration, predictor
residuals on a calibration split define conformal radii or regions, which can
then be used by a planner or shield to reject unsafe actions. This follows the
initial survey conclusion that prediction uncertainty must be preserved across module
boundaries. Since the repository does not contain final closed-loop safety
results, this report evaluates the prediction and world-model components and
leaves full navigation validation as future work.

Benjamin's component sits at this boundary. The nominal PPO/diffusion-policy
planner is responsible for proposing robot actions, while the safety interface
uses predicted pedestrian occupancies and calibrated residuals to decide whether
the action is acceptable. The interface is modular: it can consume
the Transformer's Gaussian mean and residual calibration, Trajectron++ samples,
or the diffusion predictor's sampled futures. This lets the group test how
prediction format affects downstream safety once full closed-loop experiments
are run.

