\section{Experimental Setup}

\subsection{Synthetic Generation Setup}

The Social-CVAE was pretrained on SDD and fine-tuned on ETH/UCY using 8
observed and 12 future timesteps. For each ETH/UCY seed trajectory, 20 futures
were generated with latent sampling temperature 0.7. The quality-control test
compared unfiltered generation with angle-based filtering. In the filtered
setting, the model generated extra candidates with a multiplier of 5 and kept
samples closest to the ETH/UCY turning-angle target of about $46^\circ$, within
a $20^\circ$ to $90^\circ$ range.

Evaluation used both prediction and realism metrics. ADE, FDE, minADE@20, and
minFDE@20 were computed in the normalised evaluation space. Speed,
acceleration, and turning-angle statistics compared real and generated
trajectories.

\subsection{World Model Setup}

The residual crowd world model was evaluated on a leave-one-scene-out ETH/UCY
setup with eth held out. Training used the remaining ETH/UCY scenes and filtered
synthetic trajectories. The comparison includes constant velocity, a Simple Residual Model
using only the target trajectory, a Social Residual Model using neighbouring
pedestrian context, and a Latent Crowd World Model with higher capacity. ADE
and FDE were reported in metres.

\subsection{Predictor Benchmark Setup}

The main predictor benchmark uses ETH~\cite{pellegrini2009you} scenes eth and
hotel, UCY~\cite{lerner2007crowds} scenes univ, zara1, and zara2, and SDD
scenes from the Stanford Drone Dataset~\cite{robicquet2016learning}. ETH/UCY is
sampled at 2.5 Hz with 8 observed and 12 predicted steps. SDD is downsampled
from 30 fps to 2.5 Hz using stride 12 and converted from pixels to metres at
0.0417 m/px.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{Datasets and splits used in the report.}
\label{tab:datasets}
\centering
\scriptsize
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.12}
\begin{tabularx}{\columnwidth}{@{}p{1.35cm}X p{1.55cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Dataset} & \textbf{Use in this project} & \textbf{Split} \\
\midrule
ETH/UCY & Target pedestrian benchmark for all main predictor and residual-model results. & Leave-one-scene-out \\
SDD & Large-scale pretraining source and broader motion distribution for transfer learning. & Leave-one-scene-out \\
Synthetic & Social-CVAE generated trajectories filtered by turning behaviour and used for augmentation. & Train only \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

The evaluation uses leave-one-scene-out splits. Metrics are ADE and FDE, which measure
mean and final Euclidean error; minADE@20 and minFDE@20, which evaluate the
best of 20 samples; and NLL for probabilistic Gaussian outputs. All learned
models use Adam with learning rate $10^{-3}$, weight decay $10^{-4}$, batch
size 64, and ReduceLROnPlateau scheduling. Fine-tuning uses learning rate
$10^{-4}$, patience 15, and gradient clipping at 1.0.

The metrics answer different questions. ADE and FDE measure whether the most
likely forecast is geometrically close to the true path. minADE@20 and
minFDE@20 measure whether a model can sample at least one plausible future that
matches the realised motion. NLL measures whether the model assigns probability
mass appropriately, which matters for calibrated safety filtering. This
multi-metric setup follows directly from the initial survey finding that no single
forecasting score captures planning risk.

\section{Results and Discussion}

\subsection{Synthetic Data Generation Results}

Table~\ref{tab:synthetic_generation_results} shows that the Social-CVAE can
reconstruct and sample trajectories with very low normalised prediction error.
The speed mean is close to the real ETH/UCY value, but acceleration variance is
higher and generated turning angles are smoother than real trajectories.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Synthetic trajectory generation results. Lower ADE/FDE values are better.}
\label{tab:synthetic_generation_results}
\resizebox{\columnwidth}{!}{
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Real} & \textbf{Synthetic / Model} \\
\midrule
ADE & --- & $4.61 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
FDE & --- & $8.50 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
minADE@20 & --- & $4.59 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
minFDE@20 & --- & $7.72 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
\midrule
Speed Mean & $7.49 \times 10^{-4}$ & $8.02 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
Speed Std. & $8.16 \times 10^{-4}$ & $1.13 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
Acceleration Mean & $6.33 \times 10^{-4}$ & $4.77 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
Acceleration Std. & $7.77 \times 10^{-4}$ & $1.74 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
Turning Angle Mean & $46.4^\circ$ & $28.8^\circ$ \\
Turning Angle Std. & $42.1^\circ$ & $40.3^\circ$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
}
\end{table}

The main limitation is turning behaviour. The synthetic turning-angle mean is
$28.8^\circ$, compared with $46.4^\circ$ for real trajectories, which means the
generator tends to produce smoother paths. Angle filtering improved the exported
set's mean turning angle from $15.9^\circ$ to $21.4^\circ$ in Vaibhav's
analysis, but it did not fully match the real distribution. The result supports
a limited claim: filtered synthetic trajectories can expand training diversity,
but real ETH/UCY trajectories must remain the anchor distribution.

The speed and acceleration statistics explain why the augmentation is still
valuable. The generated speed mean, $8.02\times10^{-4}$, is close to the real
mean, $7.49\times10^{-4}$, so the generator preserves the overall motion scale.
At the same time, the acceleration standard deviation is higher than the real
value, which indicates that the sampled set contains additional local motion
variation. This variation needs quality control: too little would duplicate
ETH/UCY, while too much would corrupt the data distribution. The angle filter
provides that control.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \IfFileExists{figures/seed_diversity_grid_0_3.png}{%
    \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{figures/seed_diversity_grid_0_3.png}%
  }{%
