\subsection{Residual Crowd World Model Results}

The residual world model improves over constant velocity on held-out eth
(Table~\ref{tab:residual_model_results}). The Simple Residual Model reduces ADE
from 1.0755 m to 0.9514 m and FDE from 2.2819 m to 1.9171 m, giving relative
improvements of 11.5 percent and 16.0 percent.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Residual crowd world model results on held-out eth after fine-tuning
with real ETH/UCY and filtered synthetic trajectories.}
\label{tab:residual_model_results}
\resizebox{\columnwidth}{!}{
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Model} & \textbf{ADE (m)} & \textbf{FDE (m)} & \textbf{ADE Imp.} & \textbf{FDE Imp.} \\
\midrule
Constant Velocity & 1.0755 & 2.2819 & --- & --- \\
Simple Residual Model & \textbf{0.9514} & \textbf{1.9171} & \textbf{11.5\%} & \textbf{16.0\%} \\
Social Residual Model & 1.0069 & 2.0752 & 6.4\% & 9.1\% \\
Latent Crowd World Model & Worse than CV & Worse than CV & --- & --- \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
}
\end{table}

The result supports the residual formulation in Eq.~\eqref{eq:residual_model}.
Constant velocity captures much of the local pedestrian motion, and the learned
residual corrects the cases where people slow, turn, or deviate. The Social
Residual Model also improves over constant velocity, but it underperforms the
simpler model. This suggests that neighbour context was not automatically
beneficial in the held-out eth split; the additional capacity may have learned
scene-specific patterns from the training and synthetic data. The Latent Crowd
World Model performing worse than constant velocity reinforces the same point:
larger models do not automatically generalise better.

This negative result is important for system design. More social context does
not guarantee better prediction; context quality and model capacity both
matter. If neighbour identities are sparse, noisy, or only weakly informative,
the social branch can add variance without adding predictive signal. For a
downstream planner, the simple residual model has a clearer failure mode: it
stays close to constant velocity unless the target history supports a
correction. This behaviour is easier to combine with safety filtering than a
larger model that may produce confident but poorly generalised deviations.

The limitation is that the evaluation uses one held-out scene. The result
should not be treated as a general claim of world-model superiority until the
comparison is repeated across all five ETH/UCY splits and includes a real-only
versus real-plus-synthetic ablation.

The training curves in Fig.~\ref{fig:residual_training_curves} are included for
this reason. Both residual variants reached their best validation behaviour
early, after which training error could continue improving without reliably
improving held-out performance. Early stopping is therefore part of the
generalisation strategy for a small-scene
pedestrian benchmark.

