\subsection{ETH/UCY Predictor Results}

Table~\ref{tab:ethucy} compares all trajectory predictors on ETH/UCY. The
Transformer gives the lowest ADE at 0.568 m and the lowest NLL at 1.54. The
diffusion model gives the lowest FDE at 1.195 m. Trajectron++ gives the best
minADE@20 at 0.385 m, showing that its CVAE latent variable covers diverse
future modes better than the other models.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{ETH/UCY leave-one-out results averaged over five scenes.
mADE/mFDE denote minADE@20/minFDE@20. Best values are bold.}
\label{tab:ethucy}
\centering
\footnotesize
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{3.5pt}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrrrr@{}}
\toprule
Model & ADE & FDE & mADE & mFDE & NLL \\
\midrule
CV Baseline & 0.736 & 1.272 & 0.610 & 0.814 & --- \\
Social-LSTM~\cite{alahi2016social} & 0.596 & 1.248 & 0.581 & 0.597 & 18.0 \\
SLSTM+V & 0.585 & 1.240 & 0.587 & 0.585 & 36.2 \\
Social-GRU & 0.586 & 1.238 & 0.596 & 0.924 & --- \\
Transformer & \textbf{0.568} & 1.203 & 0.638 & \textbf{0.532} & \textbf{1.54} \\
Diffusion & 0.579 & \textbf{1.195} & 1.174 & 2.032 & 5.14 \\
Trajectron++~\cite{salzmann2020trajectron} & 0.853 & 1.817 & \textbf{0.385} & 0.674 & 8.49 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{Per-scene ETH/UCY ADE. Best value per scene is bold.}
\label{tab:per_scene_ade}
\centering
\scriptsize
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrrrrr@{}}
\toprule
Scene & CV & SLSTM & SLSTM+V & T++ & Trans. & Diff. \\
\midrule
eth & 1.204 & 1.015 & 1.010 & 1.355 & \textbf{0.982} & \textbf{0.982} \\
hotel & 0.552 & 0.541 & 0.527 & 0.977 & \textbf{0.437} & 0.485 \\
univ & 0.716 & 0.655 & 0.635 & 0.772 & 0.568 & \textbf{0.563} \\
zara1 & 0.623 & 0.447 & \textbf{0.432} & 0.624 & 0.481 & 0.503 \\
zara2 & 0.583 & \textbf{0.319} & 0.320 & 0.535 & 0.371 & 0.361 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

These results show why one metric is not enough. ADE rewards the most accurate
central prediction, where the Transformer performs best. minADE@20 rewards
having at least one sample close to the true future, where Trajectron++ is
best. For safety-aware navigation, both matter: a small average error can
shrink conformal radii, but missing plausible alternative futures can still
create unsafe overconfidence.

The NLL result is also important. The Transformer's NLL of 1.54 is much lower
than Social-LSTM's 18.0 and Trajectron++'s 8.49 in our runs. This does not mean
the Transformer is globally better for navigation, because it still has weaker
best-of-20 diversity than Trajectron++. It does mean that, under the Gaussian
head used here, the Transformer gives a sharper and better calibrated
single-distribution forecast. A downstream conformal layer would still calibrate
on residuals, but starting from a smaller and better shaped residual
distribution can reduce conservatism.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.88\columnwidth]{figures/fig_nll.png}
  \caption{Average NLL comparison on ETH/UCY for probabilistic predictors. Lower
  values indicate better likelihood under the reported output distribution.}
  \label{fig:nll}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.88\columnwidth]{figures/fig03_qualitative.png}
  \caption{Qualitative prediction on zara1. The examples show that per-scene
  behaviour can differ from the aggregate ETH/UCY ranking.}
  \label{fig:qualitative}
\end{figure}

Velocity augmentation gives a small but consistent gain over Social-LSTM:
average ADE falls from 0.596 m to 0.585 m. Social-GRU nearly matches
Social-LSTM, suggesting that the shared social-pooling radius may be more
limiting than the recurrent cell choice. The diffusion predictor becomes
competitive after sharing the encoder with the Gaussian head, but its
best-of-20 diversity remains weak, so its samples cluster around the mean
rather than covering alternative futures.

Scene-level behaviour matters. The eth scene is hardest for almost every model,
with ADE near or above 1 m, while zara2 is much easier because motion is more
regular. This affects system deployment because calibration sets should
match the target environment. A safety radius calibrated mostly on easy scenes
would likely be too small for eth-like movement; a radius calibrated only on the
hardest scene would be safe but more conservative elsewhere.

The per-scene table also prevents overclaiming from the average alone. The
Transformer has the best average ADE, but it is not best on every scene:
SLSTM+V performs best on zara1, Social-LSTM narrowly wins on zara2, and diffusion
matches or beats the Transformer on eth and univ. This variation matters for
the final safety system because it suggests no predictor should be trusted
without scene-aware calibration.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{Diffusion ablation on ETH/UCY. Removing the encoder detach made the
diffusion model usable as a predictor without improving diversity.}
\label{tab:diffusion_ablation}
\centering
\footnotesize
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{4pt}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrrr@{}}
\toprule
Version & ADE & FDE & minADE@20 & NLL \\
\midrule
Detached encoder, $\lambda=1.0$ & 1.370 & 2.539 & 1.143 & 3.31 \\
Shared encoder, $\lambda=0.3$ & \textbf{0.579} & \textbf{1.195} & 1.174 & 5.14 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The diffusion ablation is one of the clearest implementation lessons. The
initial detached-encoder design separated the Gaussian head from the denoising
training signal too strongly, producing poor point prediction. Sharing the
encoder restored ADE and FDE, but minADE@20 stayed high. In other words, the
fix made diffusion accurate around the dominant future, not genuinely
multi-modal in the way Trajectron++ is.

\subsection{SDD Results}

Table~\ref{tab:sdd} reports SDD leave-one-out results. Every learned model
improves over constant velocity by a wide margin. SLSTM+V gives the best ADE,
minADE@20, and minFDE@20, while the Transformer gives the best FDE. The
diffusion model again has poor diversity, with minADE@20 equal to 1.710 m.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{SDD leave-one-out results averaged over eight scenes. Best values are bold.}
\label{tab:sdd}
\centering
\footnotesize
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{3.5pt}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrrrr@{}}
\toprule
Model & ADE & FDE & mADE & mFDE & NLL \\
\midrule
CV Baseline & 0.926 & 1.620 & 0.797 & 1.154 & --- \\
Social-LSTM & 0.672 & 1.358 & 0.783 & 0.621 & \textbf{1.162} \\
SLSTM+V & \textbf{0.656} & 1.340 & \textbf{0.755} & \textbf{0.604} & 1.289 \\
Social-GRU & 0.667 & 1.379 & 0.793 & 0.625 & 1.331 \\
Transformer & 0.657 & \textbf{1.326} & 0.808 & 0.633 & 1.474 \\
Diffusion & 0.673 & 1.335 & 1.710 & 3.159 & 1.683 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

SDD is larger and more varied than ETH/UCY, so the results also test whether
the models remain stable at scale. The recurrent models benefit more from
explicit velocity on SDD than on ETH/UCY, likely because SDD includes more
turning and speed variation. Transformer performance remains strong but no
longer separates from the recurrent models as much as it does on ETH/UCY.

The SDD results also help explain why transfer is not uniformly beneficial.
SDD supplies many more trajectories, but its aerial viewpoint, broader scene
types, and mixed agent behaviours do not perfectly match ETH/UCY. Pretraining
therefore learns transferable low-level motion patterns while still requiring
target-domain fine-tuning before evaluation on ETH/UCY.

\subsection{Transfer and Fine-Tuning}

Table~\ref{tab:finetune} compares scratch ETH/UCY training with SDD pretraining
followed by ETH/UCY and synthetic fine-tuning. The recurrent models improve by
5 to 10 percent. The Transformer barely changes, moving from 0.568 m to 0.570
m. Diffusion improves on ADE but not on diversity.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{SDD pretraining then ETH/UCY and synthetic fine-tuning. Values are
ETH/UCY ADE in metres averaged over five scenes.}
\label{tab:finetune}
\centering
\footnotesize
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{4pt}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrr@{}}
\toprule
Model & Scratch & SDD then Synth FT & $\Delta$ (\%) \\
\midrule
Social-LSTM & 0.596 & \textbf{0.537} & $-9.9$ \\
SLSTM+V & 0.585 & 0.555 & $-5.1$ \\
Social-GRU & 0.586 & 0.549 & $-6.3$ \\
Transformer & \textbf{0.568} & 0.570 & $+0.4$ \\
Diffusion & 0.579 & 0.535 & $-7.6$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

This supports a practical conclusion: transfer helps most when the architecture
still needs broad motion regularisation. The recurrent models use SDD as a
regulariser and then adapt to ETH/UCY. The Transformer already extracts most of
the relevant pattern from the small ETH/UCY training set, so the extra data does
not help. This aligns with transfer-learning evidence that more source data
helps only when the source and target structure match the model being
fine-tuned~\cite{kornblith2019better}.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.88\columnwidth]{figures/fig_generalisation.png}
  \caption{Fine-tuning comparison showing that SDD pretraining helps recurrent
  models more than the Transformer under the current protocol.}
  \label{fig:generalisation}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Integrated Discussion}

The three completed parts fit together. Synthetic data broadens the training
support, but must be filtered because unfiltered generation can distort turning
statistics. The residual world model gives a simple planning-facing motion
model, and the held-out eth result shows that a learned correction over
constant velocity improves prediction. Muhammad's predictor benchmark then separates
point accuracy, diversity, and calibration: the Transformer is the best point
predictor and gives the lowest NLL, while Trajectron++ is better at covering
multiple possible futures.

The open problem is closed-loop validation. A conformal or PPO safety-planning
layer cannot simply consume the best ADE model and assume safety follows.
Prediction errors must be calibrated, uncertainty must be composed over agents
and timesteps, and the resulting safety sets must still leave feasible motion.
This is exactly why the world model and predictor benchmark should be treated
as components of a navigation stack, not as isolated leaderboards.

\subsection{How The Components Answer The Objectives}

The original project objective was safe and efficient navigation in human
crowds. The completed work does not yet prove closed-loop navigation safety,
but it builds the part of the stack that determines what the planner believes
about people. That belief is central: if the predicted pedestrian motion is
wrong, every downstream safety decision is made from the wrong state of the
world. The current report therefore answers a narrower but necessary question:
which prediction and world-model components are suitable inputs to a safety
aware navigation system?

The synthetic generator addresses data scarcity. ETH/UCY is valuable because it
is a standard benchmark, but it is too small to cover the crowd configurations a
robot might encounter. The Social-CVAE gives a way to generate additional
future trajectories conditioned on observed motion. Its limitation, smoother
turning behaviour, is not a failure of the idea; it is evidence that synthetic
data needs distributional checks before being trusted. For this reason, the report
evaluates speed, acceleration, and turning statistics rather than only ADE.

The residual world model addresses planning speed and interpretability. A
planner does not always need a heavy distributional model at every control
cycle. It may need a fast estimate of how nearby pedestrians will move if the
robot proposes an action. The residual formulation is attractive because its
failure mode is easier to reason about than a fully learned black-box forecast:
the output equals constant velocity plus a correction. When the correction
becomes large, the planner or safety layer can treat the forecast as less
trustworthy.

The predictor benchmark addresses accuracy, diversity, and calibration. The
Transformer is a strong candidate when the downstream system wants a sharp mean
forecast and compact uncertainty. Trajectron++ is a stronger candidate when the
downstream system needs to cover multiple plausible futures. The diffusion
model provides an implementation lesson: stochastic generation alone does
not guarantee meaningful diversity. If conditioning overwhelms the denoising
process, the model may generate many samples clustered around the same mean.

Benjamin's safety/planning interface ties these findings back to robot control.
For the interface, the key question is not simply which model has the
lowest ADE. A PPO policy may propose a smooth and efficient action, but the
safety interface needs to know whether that action remains safe under the
forecasted pedestrian uncertainty. The predictor format changes this check. A
Gaussian predictor supports residual-radius calibration; a sample-based model
supports hulls or empirical occupancy; a multi-modal GMM supports level-set
style reasoning. The report therefore prepares the comparison Benjamin needs
for choosing which predictor output to connect to the planner.

\subsection{Planned Closed-Loop Evaluation}

The next experimental step is to run the same predictor choices inside a
navigation simulator. Each episode should place the robot in a start-goal task
with moving pedestrians. At each control cycle, the predictor receives the
recent pedestrian histories, the nominal PPO/diffusion policy proposes an
action, and the safety interface either accepts that action or replaces it with
a safer one. This setup would directly test whether the open-loop differences
reported here matter for robot behaviour.

The first closed-loop metric should be collision rate. It is the most basic
safety measure, but it is not sufficient by itself. A robot that never collides
because it refuses to move has failed the navigation task. The second metric should therefore be
success rate or time-to-goal. The third should be freezing rate, measured as the
fraction of time the robot remains nearly stationary despite having a reachable
goal. The initial survey identified conservatism as a common failure
mode of safer systems.

The fourth metric should be intervention frequency. If the safety interface
overrides the nominal policy at nearly every timestep, the predictor and policy
are not aligned. If it never intervenes, the safety layer may be too weak or the
test scenarios too easy. A successful system should have low collisions, reasonable
time-to-goal, and interventions concentrated in genuinely risky scenes.

The fifth metric should be achieved control rate. A predictor that is accurate
but slow can cause stale decisions. The benchmark should therefore report the
end-to-end time per control cycle, not only the model forward-pass time. This
will make it possible to compare the lightweight residual world model,
Transformer predictor, Trajectron++ samples, and diffusion samples under the
same real-time budget.

Finally, the closed-loop evaluation should include degraded sensing. Occlusions
and missed detections are normal in crowds. Testing only with perfect
pedestrian tracks would overstate safety. A practical evaluation should remove
or perturb some pedestrian observations and then measure whether the conformal
safety interface remains robust or becomes overly conservative.

\subsection{Limitations and Remaining Work}

Several limitations affect the strength of the conclusions. First, ETH/UCY is a
small benchmark. Leave-one-scene-out testing helps, but five scenes cannot cover
the full variety of real crowd behaviour. The synthetic generator addresses
data scarcity, yet its smoother turning distribution shows that synthetic data
can also introduce bias. A stronger augmentation study would compare real-only,
real-plus-unfiltered-synthetic, and real-plus-filtered-synthetic training across
all ETH/UCY scenes.

Second, the residual world model was evaluated only on held-out eth in the
current report. The result is promising because it improves over constant
velocity, but it should be repeated across hotel, univ, zara1, and zara2 before
being treated as a general dynamics model. The fact that the social residual
model underperforms the simpler residual model also deserves more analysis:
neighbour context may help only in specific density regimes, or the pooling
method may be too crude to represent interaction cues.

Third, the predictor benchmark is open-loop. It measures future trajectory
accuracy given observed pedestrian histories, but it does not yet measure what
happens when a robot acts on those forecasts. In closed loop, a small prediction
delay, a missed pedestrian, or a conservative conformal radius can change
navigation behaviour. The next evaluation should therefore report collision
rate, time-to-goal, intervention frequency, planner latency, and freezing rate
with Benjamin's safety interface connected.

Finally, the current work treats perception as already solved. Real robots must
track people under occlusions, noisy detections, identity switches, and limited
field of view. Those errors would change both the predictor input and the
safety calibration residuals. A deployment-ready system should therefore
calibrate not only trajectory prediction error, but also tracking and execution
error.

\section{Conclusions}

This report presents the design and evaluation work completed so far for safe
robot navigation in human crowds. Vaibhav's Social-CVAE generator produces
synthetic trajectories that can augment ETH/UCY, but the generated turning
statistics show why filtering is necessary. His residual crowd world model
improves over constant velocity on held-out eth, reducing ADE by 11.5 percent
and FDE by 16.0 percent. This supports its use as a lightweight dynamics model
for planning-facing pedestrian forecasts, although the evidence should be extended
to all ETH/UCY splits.

Muhammad's predictor benchmark shows that model choice depends strongly on the
metric. The Transformer gives the best ETH/UCY point accuracy and NLL, with ADE
0.568 m and NLL 1.54. Trajectron++ gives the best multi-modal coverage, with
minADE@20 0.385 m. Diffusion becomes competitive on ADE/FDE after the shared
encoder fix, but its samples still lack diversity. SDD pretraining improves
recurrent models by 5 to 10 percent, while the Transformer gains little.

The main lesson is that prediction quality is multi-dimensional. A safe crowd
navigation system needs data diversity, a planning-facing world model,
accurate point forecasts, calibrated uncertainty, and closed-loop validation.
The next step is to connect these prediction outputs to Benjamin's
conformal/PPO safety-planning interface and evaluate the full stack under
collision, efficiency, latency, and conservatism metrics.

